---
import Layout from '../layouts/Layout.astro';
import TopBar from '../components/TopBar.astro';
import Header from '../components/Header.astro';
import PageHero from '../components/PageHero.astro';
import CtaBanner from '../components/CtaBanner.astro';
import Footer from '../components/Footer.astro';

const categories = [
  {
    id: 'benefits',
    label: 'Benefits',
    faqs: [
      {
        q: 'What is the biggest financial advantage of a green roof?',
        a: 'The primary financial benefit is extension of the lifetime of the roof — typical estimates are that a green roof potentially extends the lifetime of a roof between 200 and 300 percent, by protecting the rooftop from ultraviolet radiation, large temperature fluctuations, drying winds, and punctures. Additionally, reduced membrane maintenance brings significant cost savings over time. Stormwater incentives may provide substantial monetary benefits in some communities.',
      },
      {
        q: 'What incentives are available for green roofs?',
        a: 'Many cities and states offer financial incentives for green roofs to reduce stormwater runoff and encourage energy conservation. Tax credits, fee avoidance for impervious surfaces, grant funding, and favorable zoning are commonly available. Check with state and local governments for programs in your area.',
      },
      {
        q: 'How do green roofs save energy?',
        a: 'Green roofs have been proven to bring about significant energy savings, particularly during the summer cooling season in which single story buildings can experience a reduction of greater than 25% energy use for air conditioning. Green roof soils insulate roofs from heat while plants transform heat and soil moisture into humidity for evaporative cooling. Each gallon of water transpired by the plants or evaporated from the soil surface liberates 8,000 BTU of thermal energy.',
      },
      {
        q: 'How does the LiveRoof system reduce stormwater runoff?',
        a: 'In urban areas, as much as 75% of rainwater runs into sewer systems carrying contaminants from the air and roadways. LiveRoof green roof surfaces absorb substantial rainfall, reduce runoff, lessen combined sewer overflow risks, and filter water percolating through soil. Even excess rainfall is filtered and delayed until after peak flows, allowing additional sewer system capacity.',
      },
      {
        q: 'How do green roofs reduce noise?',
        a: 'Plants, soil, and trapped air and moisture in the soil are great acoustic insulators. Studies have shown that green roofs can reduce indoor sound by as much as 40 decibels, providing significant benefits for those near overhead highways and airports.',
      },
      {
        q: 'What is the urban heat island effect?',
        a: 'The urban heat island effect represents the temperature difference between urban areas and their surroundings. Urban areas are from 7 to 10 degrees hotter due to the concentration of heat-absorbing buildings, pavement, auto-exhaust, and hot air from cooling systems. The LiveRoof system acts like a protective umbrella above the roof to shade and insulate buildings, avoiding the heat island effect associated with traditional rooftops.',
      },
    ],
  },
  {
    id: 'design',
    label: 'Design',
    faqs: [
      {
        q: 'What waterproofing systems can LiveRoof work with?',
        a: 'LiveRoof systems are compatible with nearly all waterproofing types: EPDM, TPO, PVC, bituminous, polyurethane, rubberized asphalt, inverted or conventional. We work with all appropriate waterproofing products from all manufacturers. In every case, the manufacturer\'s "approved LiveRoof-compatible build up" should be specified and followed.',
      },
      {
        q: 'Why does LiveRoof recommend overhead spray irrigation?',
        a: 'Spray rotor systems are the least expensive to install, easiest to maintain, and apply water most efficiently. Green roof soils are predominantly composed of inorganic aggregates with poor capillary qualities, which means drip or sub-irrigation systems require excessive emitter density or use more water overall. Research by Dr. Bradley Rowe at Michigan State University found that drip and sub-irrigation systems wasted more than double the water lost in an overhead spray irrigation system.',
      },
      {
        q: 'Does LiveRoof need irrigation?',
        a: 'The need for supplemental irrigation depends on plants selected, local climate, weather patterns, roof slope, and system type. In the north temperate zone, irrigation may seldom be required, but a backup system is recommended for prolonged hot, dry, windy, sunny weather. Irrigating even once per month during protracted dry weather can keep your green roof looking its best. In predictably hot and dry regions, always incorporate irrigation into the design.',
      },
      {
        q: 'How much does the LiveRoof system weigh?',
        a: 'The LiveRoof system weighs approximately 27–29 lbs/sq ft (with a media depth of 4") when fully vegetated and saturated. The soil follows FLL standards with enhanced sustainable organic content, intentionally avoiding excessive organics that shrink from decomposition or perlite that breaks down during freeze-thaw cycles.',
      },
      {
        q: 'Can I retrofit my existing building with a green roof?',
        a: 'Retrofitting depends on structural weight-bearing capacity. A qualified structural engineer must always be consulted before installation. The LiveRoof Lite system was developed for existing buildings, featuring 2.5" of soil with saturated weight of 15–17 lbs/sq ft, expanding green roof opportunities on older structures.',
      },
      {
        q: 'Where can the LiveRoof system be used?',
        a: 'LiveRoof is most commonly used on well-drained, low and mid-slope roofs atop industrial, commercial, institutional, governmental, and residential buildings that can support green roof weight. Green roofs must only be installed on appropriately engineered buildings.',
      },
      {
        q: 'Can the LiveRoof system be used in non-roof areas?',
        a: 'Yes, LiveRoof modules can instantly landscape median strips, patios, plazas, and malls with fully mature ground covers.',
      },
      {
        q: 'Can LiveRoof be used in elevated planters?',
        a: 'Yes, typically on rooftop patios where load limits prevent substantial soil volumes. Fill planters with closed-cell foam except the top 4.5–6.5 inches, then set LiveRoof modules on top for visual soil depth appearance.',
      },
    ],
  },
  {
    id: 'installation',
    label: 'Installation',
    faqs: [
      {
        q: 'How do I go about having a LiveRoof system installed?',
        a: 'Contact your LiveRoof local grower or call LiveRoof at 1-800-875-1392 or email sales@LiveRoof.com. For Ontario and Atlantic Canada, contact Kees Govers at (519) 671-5777 or kees@liveroofontario.ca.',
      },
      {
        q: 'How can a contractor become a LiveRoof Certified Installer?',
        a: 'Landscape and roofing contractors interested in offering LiveRoof installation services should contact their local representative. LiveRoof has developed an online training program for contractors on their first project covering product, installation, and maintenance specifications. Before the first project installation, LiveRoof representatives conduct in-person training with the job site foreman and installation team.',
      },
      {
        q: 'Can LiveRoof modules be cut to fit odd dimensions and angles?',
        a: 'Yes, LiveRoof modules can be cut to size and shape using a masonry saw or reciprocating saw. When custom cutting LiveRoof modules, the cut side should abut the non-cut side of another module, in order to contain the soil and minimize the work of installation. The cut side should not abut edging on the low, draining side of the roof.',
      },
    ],
  },
  {
    id: 'maintenance',
    label: 'Maintenance',
    faqs: [
      {
        q: 'Why are frequent, brief maintenance activities critical to success?',
        a: 'The life cycle of most weeds is about four weeks. Therefore, by weeding every 2 weeks, for just a few minutes, the few weeds that come from birds and the wind are not allowed to reproduce. Lean, preventative maintenance is far more effective and economical than reactive maintenance.',
      },
      {
        q: 'How long should I set my automatic irrigation timer?',
        a: 'Measure your system\'s output using rain gauges or tuna cans placed in a line from the sprinkler. Run sprinklers for 15 minutes, measure water depth, then calculate the duration needed for your target depth (typically one inch). Adjust based on your green roof\'s specific needs.',
      },
      {
        q: 'Is it okay to walk on green roof plantings?',
        a: 'Minimal, sparse walking is acceptable — one person a couple times weekly. Avoid creating single paths, standing in one place, or trampling plants. Wait until foliage is dry before servicing equipment, and cover plants with plywood or foam for up to four hours. Avoid foot traffic when plants are wet or frozen.',
      },
      {
        q: 'Will I need to fertilize my green roof?',
        a: 'Yes, but likely not annually. Send soil samples to a lab qualified for green roof soils each spring before growth begins. If nitrogen levels are low, apply controlled-release fertilizer. Application rates typically range from 1.5 to 3.0 pounds of actual nitrogen per 1,000 square feet.',
      },
      {
        q: 'Can I use de-icing chemicals on my LiveRoof plants during the winter?',
        a: 'No, LiveRoof plants are damaged by de-icing chemicals. Use sand or cat litter instead for anti-slip measures after shoveling.',
      },
      {
        q: 'Can LiveRoof modules be lifted to access the roof membrane?',
        a: 'Yes. Use a flat-bladed shovel to locate container edges, peel away plant material, then use pliers to lift modules. Replace modules when finished. Never use sharp instruments around roof membranes.',
      },
      {
        q: 'Can I use my green roof as a dog run?',
        a: 'Dog urine and excrement kill succulent plants. Green roofs specifically developed for dog traffic use turf grass or lily-turf species like Liriope, requiring minimum six inches of soil. Pick up excrement and water regularly to flush urine from soil.',
      },
    ],
  },
  {
    id: 'plants-soil',
    label: 'Plants & Soil',
    faqs: [
      {
        q: 'What are the best plants to use on green roofs?',
        a: 'In the Lite and Standard systems, we recommend plants with extreme drought resistance — succulent, water-holding plants like Sedums, Alliums, Sempervivums, and Delospermas. The best LiveRoof plants employ Crassulacean Acid Metabolism (CAM), making them up to ten times more efficient with water conservation than non-CAM plants. In the Deep and Maxx systems with irrigation, a broader plant palette is possible. Consult your local LiveRoof representative for climate-specific recommendations.',
      },
      {
        q: 'Can I grow vegetables or fruits in a rooftop garden?',
        a: 'Yes. Numerous vegetables, herbs, and select fruits (such as strawberries and melons) may be grown on intensive green roofs that receive frequent watering, have ample sunlight, and have proper soil. Edible plants require sufficient nutrients to support their rapid growth cycle. A blend of organic soil and traditional green roof growing media yields the best results, but the soil will need annual amendments to maintain volume and provide sufficient nutrition.',
      },
      {
        q: 'What is so special about LiveRoof soil?',
        a: 'LiveRoof Engineered Green Roof Soil is composed of approximately 94% high quality inorganic aggregates by dry weight. It includes clay particles for nutrient binding and acid rain buffering, plus disease-suppressive organic material. The soil conforms to German FLL granulometric standards, filters rainwater, effectively grows LiveRoof plants, and is designed to last for many decades. Soil specifications vary somewhat by region depending on climate, water quality, and available components.',
      },
    ],
  },
];
---

<Layout title="FAQ – LiveRoof Green Roof Systems">
  <TopBar />
  <Header />

  <PageHero
    eyebrow="FAQ"
    title="Frequently Asked"
    highlight="Questions"
    subtitle="Find answers to the most common questions about LiveRoof green roof systems, design, installation, maintenance, and more."
    breadcrumbs={[
      { label: 'Home', href: '/' },
      { label: 'FAQ' },
    ]}
  />

  <section class="py-14 md:py-24 bg-white">
    <div class="container">
      <!-- Tab Navigation -->
      <div class="faq-tabs flex flex-wrap gap-2 mb-12 border-b border-border pb-4" role="tablist">
        {categories.map((cat, i) => (
          <button
            class={`faq-tab px-5 py-2.5 rounded-lg text-[0.85rem] font-semibold tracking-wide transition-all cursor-pointer ${i === 0 ? 'bg-green text-white' : 'bg-mid text-text-muted hover:bg-border'}`}
            data-tab={cat.id}
            role="tab"
            aria-selected={i === 0 ? 'true' : 'false'}
          >
            {cat.label}
          </button>
        ))}
      </div>

      <!-- Tab Panels -->
      {categories.map((cat, i) => (
        <div
          class={`faq-panel ${i === 0 ? '' : 'hidden'}`}
          data-panel={cat.id}
          role="tabpanel"
        >
          <div class="grid gap-6">
            {cat.faqs.map((faq) => (
              <details class="group bg-mid rounded-xl overflow-hidden">
                <summary class="flex items-center justify-between cursor-pointer px-4 sm:px-7 py-5 text-dark font-semibold text-[1rem] leading-snug select-none list-none [&::-webkit-details-marker]:hidden">
                  <span class="pr-4">{faq.q}</span>
                  <svg class="flex-shrink-0 w-5 h-5 text-text-muted transition-transform group-open:rotate-45" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2" viewBox="0 0 24 24">
                    <path d="M12 5v14M5 12h14" />
                  </svg>
                </summary>
                <div class="px-4 sm:px-7 pb-6 pt-0">
                  <p class="text-text-muted leading-relaxed">{faq.a}</p>
                </div>
              </details>
            ))}
          </div>
        </div>
      ))}
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Contact CTA -->
  <section class="py-10 md:py-16 bg-mid">
    <div class="container text-center">
      <h2 class="font-serif text-[2rem] text-dark mb-4">Still Have Questions?</h2>
      <p class="text-text-muted max-w-[480px] mx-auto mb-8 leading-relaxed">
        Our team is here to help. Reach out to your local LiveRoof Ontario representative or contact global headquarters.
      </p>
      <div class="flex flex-wrap justify-center gap-4">
        <a href="/contact" class="btn btn-primary">Contact Us</a>
        <a href="tel:5196715777" class="btn btn-outline-dark">Call (519) 671-5777</a>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <CtaBanner />
  <Footer />
</Layout>

<script>
  document.addEventListener('DOMContentLoaded', () => {
    const tabs = document.querySelectorAll('.faq-tab');
    const panels = document.querySelectorAll('.faq-panel');

    tabs.forEach((tab) => {
      tab.addEventListener('click', () => {
        const target = tab.getAttribute('data-tab');

        tabs.forEach((t) => {
          t.classList.remove('bg-green', 'text-white');
          t.classList.add('bg-mid', 'text-text-muted');
          t.setAttribute('aria-selected', 'false');
        });
        tab.classList.remove('bg-mid', 'text-text-muted');
        tab.classList.add('bg-green', 'text-white');
        tab.setAttribute('aria-selected', 'true');

        panels.forEach((panel) => {
          if (panel.getAttribute('data-panel') === target) {
            panel.classList.remove('hidden');
          } else {
            panel.classList.add('hidden');
          }
        });
      });
    });
  });
</script>
